    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2975089892" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2975089892" />
    <a title="Emma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10616421-emma"><img alt="Emma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1543832955p2/10616421.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2975089892?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emma" href="/user/show/10616421-emma">Emma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143105275" href="/book/show/2675914-the-underdogs">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10616421-emma?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10616421-emma?shelf=ownvoices">ownvoices</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2975089892" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13803507467792186088">I had to read this for a history class. It was fine, the only reason it was ok was because it wasn&apos;t a book I&apos;d have chosen to read myself. <br/><br/>Mariano Azuela took part in the Mexican Revolution of 1910-1920 and drew upon those experiences when he wrote The Underdogs. The book followed a man and the group of peasant-soldiers he accumulated over the years of the revolution. I think it might have been the style of writing in the early 1900s to feel vaguely unattached to the story, because Azuela&apos;s sty</span>
  <span id="freeText13803507467792186088" style="display:none">I had to read this for a history class. It was fine, the only reason it was ok was because it wasn't a book I'd have chosen to read myself. <br /><br />Mariano Azuela took part in the Mexican Revolution of 1910-1920 and drew upon those experiences when he wrote The Underdogs. The book followed a man and the group of peasant-soldiers he accumulated over the years of the revolution. I think it might have been the style of writing in the early 1900s to feel vaguely unattached to the story, because Azuela's style reminded me of Fitzgerald and Hemingway, where something big will happen but it's not always dwelled on. <br /><br />Most of the characters are archetypes, like the women represent the pre-Revolution stereotypical woman vs. the Revolutionary women who fought and killed alongside men. The men portray the ideologues and footsoldiers of the Mexican Revolution for the most part. There was one particular man who was - even more so than the other characters - a depiction of the uncaring violence that became a staple. <br /><br />Another thing Azuela focused on was the idea that the revolutionaries who were from Chihuahua's ranches and the frontierland didn't always know why they were fighting. On the other hand, Azuela has his ideologue stand-in be all aspirational and indignant that the peasant-warriors can't articulate the class warfare that the ideologue feels the Revolution is being fought for. <br /><br />It's a cool book and an easy read. You could def go through and find more imagery and stereotypes or different interpretations. If you're interested in early 20th century novels, give this book a look. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13803507467792186088" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

