<div id="review_2194292801" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2194292801" />
    <a title="Michael Haase" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36432305-michael-haase"><img alt="Michael Haase" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1498749694p2/36432305.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2194292801?book_show_action=true">Nov 26, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Haase" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Haase" href="/user/show/36432305-michael-haase">Michael Haase</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2194292801" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16158347302133728976">It&apos;s hard to stomach a novel filled with so much violence and brutality. <i>Los de abajo</i> is like a shorter and more mild version of <i>Blood Meridian</i>, but all the same, it gets to a such a point that I imagine only sadists could derive any enjoyment from their reading. It may be said that, as a work of historical fiction, the quality of the book comes from its educational value and less from the pleasure of reading it. <br/><br/>This is a novel that preserves the atmosphere of hostility and chaos that pervaded </span>
  <span id="freeText16158347302133728976" style="display:none">It's hard to stomach a novel filled with so much violence and brutality. <i>Los de abajo</i> is like a shorter and more mild version of <i>Blood Meridian</i>, but all the same, it gets to a such a point that I imagine only sadists could derive any enjoyment from their reading. It may be said that, as a work of historical fiction, the quality of the book comes from its educational value and less from the pleasure of reading it. <br /><br />This is a novel that preserves the atmosphere of hostility and chaos that pervaded early 20th century Mexico, and consequentially excels in immersing its readers in its events, but ultimately suffers, I believe, from adopting the perspective of the rebels. These characters consist of the most despicable people I've witnessed in historical fiction. They amount to a group of ragged outcasts high on testosterone and swept up in the excitement of unrestrained crime. It's hard following a story when its protagonists are a detestable bunch. I hated almost everyone of them from Luis Cervantes to even Camilla, though I felt mostly pity for La Pintada/War-Paint.<br /><br />I also must mention I struggled reading this. I read it in Spanish, and though Spanish isn't my first language, I've had a lot of experience with Spanish writing. Nonetheless, there were far too many words I was unfamiliar with in this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16158347302133728976" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


