    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2685233346" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2685233346" />
    <a title="Abby Hinrichs" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/92159885-abby-hinrichs"><img alt="Abby Hinrichs" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2685233346?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abby Hinrichs" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abby Hinrichs" href="/user/show/92159885-abby-hinrichs">Abby Hinrichs</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2685233346" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8904334107245670069">In Mariano Azuela&apos;s novel, Los de abajo, Demetrio Marcías, an Indian farmer is roped into joining the Revolution and leaving his wife and child behind. Along the way, he meets other people who join him in his fight against the Federals and eventually help him to earn the title as one of Villa&apos;s generals. This book discusses the discrepancies that lie between the rich and the poor, the educated and the illiterate, men and women, and the Revolutionaries and the Federals (Mexican government). Chara</span>
  <span id="freeText8904334107245670069" style="display:none">In Mariano Azuela's novel, Los de abajo, Demetrio Marcías, an Indian farmer is roped into joining the Revolution and leaving his wife and child behind. Along the way, he meets other people who join him in his fight against the Federals and eventually help him to earn the title as one of Villa's generals. This book discusses the discrepancies that lie between the rich and the poor, the educated and the illiterate, men and women, and the Revolutionaries and the Federals (Mexican government). Characters such as Luis Cervantes represent the intellectual side of the revolution through his abandonment of taking the side of the Mexican government and choosing to side with Demetrio and his men before eventually pursing medicine in the United States towards the end of the book. Characters such as Pintada and Camila represent the two different roles, one active and one passive, that women played in the revolution as well. Azuela does a good job making his characters relatable in order for the reader to fully understand the complexity and struggles of the Mexican Revolution. He shows how ordinary men started out fighting against the government and for each other, but ended up having no idea what exactly it was that they were fighting for because many of them resorted to stooping to the level of the Federals in the raping and pillaging of small villages, not much different from the ones where they themselves came from. This book gave me a new understanding of what all the Mexican Revolution entailed and how it affected "Los de abajo." These people, the underdogs, those at the bottom of society, experienced the Revolution in a way that was very unique from that of the rich and those who were members of the Mexican government and this book does a great job depicting their journeys and showing how the Revolution changed the people of Mexico.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8904334107245670069" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


