<div id="review_2685379813" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2685379813" />
    <a title="Bryn McCarthy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/92159816-bryn-mccarthy"><img alt="Bryn McCarthy" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2685379813?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bryn McCarthy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bryn McCarthy" href="/user/show/92159816-bryn-mccarthy">Bryn McCarthy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2685379813" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15262918941665758086">Before reading “Los de abajo,” by Mariano Azuela, I thought it would be a historical synopsis of the Mexican Revolution, but once I began reading I quickly learned that it actually tells the story of one individuals life throughout the revolution, the life of Demetrio Macías. Demetrio begins as an Indian uninvolved in the revolution, a husband wanting to protect his wife and his land, and transforms throughout the book into one of Pancho Villa’s top generals. Furthermore, this book appeals to re</span>
  <span id="freeText15262918941665758086" style="display:none">Before reading “Los de abajo,” by Mariano Azuela, I thought it would be a historical synopsis of the Mexican Revolution, but once I began reading I quickly learned that it actually tells the story of one individuals life throughout the revolution, the life of Demetrio Macías. Demetrio begins as an Indian uninvolved in the revolution, a husband wanting to protect his wife and his land, and transforms throughout the book into one of Pancho Villa’s top generals. Furthermore, this book appeals to readers because it does not consist of strictly historical elements, it has a love story woven throughout in the form of Demetrio’s affection for Camila. But, on the other hand it also showcases the treachery and tragedy that occurred throughout this time period: rape, torture, and ravaging people’s homes, among others, which was hard to read at times but helped contextualize the revolution. The book also helps readers understand the main players of the revolution on a more personal level. Luis Cervantes, for example, encourages Demetrio to partake in the revolution and plays a key role in it, but also has intellectual layers to him. All in all Azuela does an excellent job of making the reader attached to the characters and the cause throughout the book through his use of dialogue, narration, and beautiful detail so that the ending is even more powerful (but I don’t want to go into too much detail about the ending and spoil it!). After finishing “Los de abajo” the reader will have a new appreciation for the hardships of the Mexican Revolution and, at least in my case, find themselves rooting for the underdogs. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15262918941665758086" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


