<div id="review_2685317869" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2685317869" />
    <a title="Edwin Castellanos" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/92168088-edwin-castellanos"><img alt="Edwin Castellanos" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2685317869?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edwin Castellanos" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edwin Castellanos" href="/user/show/92168088-edwin-castellanos">Edwin Castellanos</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2685317869" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13225630488176283263">Prof. Barnett / Washington and Lee University<br/><br/>Los de Abajo written by Mariano Azuela was a great novel that drew me into the world of the Mexican Revolution of 1910. I was definitely able to understand more with some knowledge of the key events and people that played a role before and during the Mexican Revolution. I don&apos;t think that a reader without some understanding of Mexico would be able to navigate the world of the main character Demetrio Macías without missing key details. The language and</span>
  <span id="freeText13225630488176283263" style="display:none">Prof. Barnett / Washington and Lee University<br /><br />Los de Abajo written by Mariano Azuela was a great novel that drew me into the world of the Mexican Revolution of 1910. I was definitely able to understand more with some knowledge of the key events and people that played a role before and during the Mexican Revolution. I don't think that a reader without some understanding of Mexico would be able to navigate the world of the main character Demetrio Macías without missing key details. The language and terms that were utilized were a peculiar usage of a regional Spanish in Mexico. Although different and difficult at times, they were fun to read and sounded very familiar to the language I've heard as a Mexican. This was an element of the novel that increased the sense of being present in Mexico. Additionally, Mariano introduced the characters with great depth at times that made me want to know more about them and those in a similar situation during the Mexican Revolution. Through the novel you learn about the situation females were in, how a "curro" was treated with "the people," and how someone in el pueblo became a revolutionary. One thing that was difficult to follow at times were the gaps in the story from chapter to chapter but Azula's story telling left me interested in reading more perspectives on the Mexican Revolution. Overall, I would recommend this book to those with some understanding of the precursors to the Mexican Revolution and interest in Mexican novels. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13225630488176283263" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


