<div id="review_2685535982" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2685535982" />
    <a title="McKinley Hamilton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/92155904-mckinley-hamilton"><img alt="McKinley Hamilton" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2685535982?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="McKinley Hamilton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="McKinley Hamilton" href="/user/show/92155904-mckinley-hamilton">McKinley Hamilton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2685535982" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5441365763809591361">Professor Barnett /Washington and Lee University: <i>Los de abajo</i> served as the first novel that I have read regarding the Mexican Revolution and I believe that it detailed a raw and insightful account of the tragedy and passion associated with this revolution. This novel allowed me to further understand the complexity of this ongoing event and demonstrated how the motivations of revolutionary leaders and fighters were multifaceted and occasionally ambiguous. The character development of Demetrio i</span>
  <span id="freeText5441365763809591361" style="display:none">Professor Barnett /Washington and Lee University: <i>Los de abajo</i> served as the first novel that I have read regarding the Mexican Revolution and I believe that it detailed a raw and insightful account of the tragedy and passion associated with this revolution. This novel allowed me to further understand the complexity of this ongoing event and demonstrated how the motivations of revolutionary leaders and fighters were multifaceted and occasionally ambiguous. The character development of Demetrio illustrated how over time his reasons behind continuing the fight became more difficult to discern, yet he remained passionate and animated until the end of novel. Additionally, I noticed how the author Mariano Azuela did not provide a romanticized account of this revolution, but rather exposed how this battle was rampant with violence towards the innocent and rampaging of their villages. Nevertheless, I understood the complex motivations of the characters as they and their predecessors had faced time periods of oppression and subjugation to exploitative authorities. Overall, I believe that this work challenged my previously held assumptions about the causes of the revolution and the magnitude to which this affected the “pueblo” of Mexico.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5441365763809591361" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


