<div id="review_2685675815" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2685675815" />
    <a title="Carissa Margraf" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/92123348-carissa-margraf"><img alt="Carissa Margraf" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2685675815?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carissa Margraf" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carissa Margraf" href="/user/show/92123348-carissa-margraf">Carissa Margraf</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2685675815" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10803328886437766695">(Carissa Margraf for Professor Barnett, Washington and Lee University) If my memory is correct, Los de Abajo was actually the first novel that I have read in Spanish in its entirety, so that presented its own challenges, but it was an extremely engaging story to keep track of. I was not sure what to expect from it, but it was so interesting to watch the progression of Demetrio&apos;s involvement with the rebels and his promotions to higher ranks, yet his lack of clarity on what exactly kept him fight</span>
  <span id="freeText10803328886437766695" style="display:none">(Carissa Margraf for Professor Barnett, Washington and Lee University) If my memory is correct, Los de Abajo was actually the first novel that I have read in Spanish in its entirety, so that presented its own challenges, but it was an extremely engaging story to keep track of. I was not sure what to expect from it, but it was so interesting to watch the progression of Demetrio's involvement with the rebels and his promotions to higher ranks, yet his lack of clarity on what exactly kept him fighting. He demonstrated obvious bravery and strength of character, often serving as a voice of reason when his men would act almost barbaric, yet he also had this internal quest to find who he is and what he's fighting for. His public image was so sure of himself, but it contrasted his reality. The ending was definitely not satisfying for me, because it seems like he never learns why he is so motivated to keep fighting until his death. But overall I really enjoyed reading Los de Abajo because it balanced the gruesome realities of revolution with seemingly "normal" things like the varying love interests and Demetrio and Camila's affections. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10803328886437766695" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

