    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2685312522" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2685312522" />
    <a title="Alexa Caffio" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76274356-alexa-caffio"><img alt="Alexa Caffio" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2685312522?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alexa Caffio" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alexa Caffio" href="/user/show/76274356-alexa-caffio">Alexa Caffio</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2685312522" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer729557159140829302">(Prof. Barnett / Washington and Lee University Winter 2019)<br/><br/><i>Los de abajo</i> by Mariano Azuela seems like a true primary source document from the Mexican revolution, despite the fictional characters and storyline. Each character is chosen deliberately to represent a different group or illustrate a possible outcome of a life during the revolution. While the language presents certain challenges due to an abundance of hundred-year-old colloquialisms, the spirit of the story shines through the action. In</span>
  <span id="freeText729557159140829302" style="display:none">(Prof. Barnett / Washington and Lee University Winter 2019)<br /><br /><i>Los de abajo</i> by Mariano Azuela seems like a true primary source document from the Mexican revolution, despite the fictional characters and storyline. Each character is chosen deliberately to represent a different group or illustrate a possible outcome of a life during the revolution. While the language presents certain challenges due to an abundance of hundred-year-old colloquialisms, the spirit of the story shines through the action. In my opinion, none of the characters were particularly likable, but they fought valiantly for their cause. Rooted in "la novela telúrica," <i>Los de abajo</i> has grown beyond the Earth to leave a lasting impact on Mexican literature.</span>
  <a data-text-id="729557159140829302" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


